<div xmlns:perseus="http://www.perseus.org/meta/perseus.rdfs#" xmlns:dctype="http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/" xmlns:tufts="http://www.tufts.edu/" xmlns:alph="http://alpheios.net/namespaces/tei" class="alpheios-lex-text_container en">
    <div class="alpheios-lex-entry" lemma-id="n4288" body-key="α">
          <b><span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἧμαι, ἧς</span></b>  (<span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">αι</span>), <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἧσται, ἥμεθα,
            ἧσθε, ἕαται</span> and <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">εἵαται</span>,
          imp. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἧσο</span>, inf. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἧσθαι</span>, part. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἥμενος</span>, ipf.
            <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἥμην, ἧστο, ἥσθην, ἥμεθα, ἧντο</span> and
            <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἕατο</span> and <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">εἵατο</span>: <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">sit;</span> often w. a part. to denote
          some condition of mind or body, <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἧστο ὀδῡρόμενος,
            θαυμάζων, ὀλιγηπελέων</span>, etc.; and, in general, the verb may
          denote a settled condition of any sort, ‘stay,’ ‘keep,’ <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἑκὰς ἥμεθα πατρίδος αἴης,</span>
          <i><span class="en">Il. 15.740</span></i>, <i><span class="en">Il. 24.542</span></i>; <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc"> σῑγῇ, ἀκέουσα, σιωπῇ
            ἧσο</span>, <i><span class="en">Il.
          4.412</span></i>.</div> <div class="alpheios-lex-footnotes en"> </div>
    <div class="alpheios-lex-alph-source">From <u>
            <u>A Homeric Dictionary</u>
        </u> (Georg Autenrieth, New York, Harper and Brothers, 1891) </div>
